@WIDTH "80"
@HEIGHT "110"
@MASTER "translators.guide"
@INDEX "MAIN"

@NODE "MAIN" "AmCEx: Locale translations"
@NEXT "HOWTO"
@PREV "MAIN"
@TOC "MAIN"


  Locale translations
  -------------------


  The two additional languages, German and Hungarian were translated
  from the original English texts by the @{"author" LINK "PROGUPDATES"}.  They may show the odd
  inaccuracy where a word couldn't be found in a dictionary, but most
  Amigans are certainly intelligent enough to understand even clumsy
  attempts at translation.

  If anyone can contribute with any other language, it would undoubtedly
  be appreciated by those in the Amiga community, who don't understand
  sufficient English to be comfortable with  having to use it every day.



                @{"How to" LINK "HOWTO"}.........translate catalogs.

                @{"The guide" LINK "THEGUIDE"}......translate the guide.

                @{"Uploads" LINK "UPLOADS"}........of translations.

                @{"List" LINK "TRANSLATORS"}...........of translators.





@ENDNODE


@NODE "HOWTO" "AmCEx: Translations - how to?"
@NEXT "THEGUIDE"
@PREV "MAIN"
@TOC "MAIN"


  How to
  ------

  To translate the program's gadgets, menu items and messages, look
  into the @{"AmCEx.ct" SYSTEM "Sys:Tools/EditPad AmCEx.ct"} (catalog translator) file.  The empty line above
  each English text, and below the (partly capitalized) label, is where
  the equivalent in the translated language should be typed in:

  MSG_ERR_NoLib

  ; Can't open v%ld of: \n %s
  ;

  In the above case, the English text contains a '%s' parameter where
  the program can insert a file name.  Another parameter is '%ld'
  which allows a decimal number to be inserted, in this case it's the
  version number of a library.  These parameters have to appear in the
  translated text too, but their position can vary, depending on the
  syntax of the particular language.

  Some of these strings have to be limited in length, the text for an
  Okay gadget for example, so the min and max lengths can be found in
  the @{"AmCEx.cd" SYSTEM "Sys:Utilities/AmigaGuide AmCEx.cd"} (catalog descriptor) file:

  MSG_ERR_Butt (/2/16)
  Okay
  ;

  MSG_ERR_Butt is the label, as used inside the program, Okay is the
  actual text that will be printed in the gadget.

  The numbers between the brackets mean that the length of the string
  has to be a minimum of 2 and a maximum of 16 characters.

  (In the case of the above example, if the word for Okay consisted of
  only a single letter in your own language, I would suggest to put a
  full stop '.' or exclamation mark '!' after it.)

  If there is nothing after the second slash '/', it means there is no
  maximum limit (but remember the actual window size), if there is
  nothing between the two slashes, then the string can be left empty.

  The space in front of the first slash '/' is internal to the program.




@ENDNODE


@NODE "THEGUIDE" "AmCEx: Translations - the guide."
@NEXT "UPLOADS"
@PREV "HOWTO"
@TOC "MAIN"


  The guide
  ---------


  In case someone wants to translate the guide, there are only a few
  points one should be aware of:


  AmigaGuide commands, ie DATABASE, WIDTH, HEIGHT, LINK, NODE, NEXT,
  PREV, TOC, ENDNODE are mostly preceeded by an '\@' sign and mostly
  capitalized.  They are to be left alone.  The same goes for the node
  names, ie MAIN, FUNCTION, REQUIREMENTS, BUGS, INSTALLATION, etc. which
  don't have to be capitalized, though I have written them as such, in
  order to make them more recognisable.

  There are some other items, usually between brackets, such as {i} and
  {ui} which will italicise the text between them, or {fg shine} and
  {fg text} which will change the colour of the text they bracket.




@ENDNODE


@NODE "UPLOADS" "AmCEx: Translations - uploading."
@NEXT "PROGUPDATES"
@PREV "THEGUIDE"
@TOC "MAIN"


  Uploads
  -------


  If someone did decide to translate either a catalog file or even the
  guide, then please attach it to @{"me" LINK "PROGUPDATES"} via email, so I can process it and
  include it in an updated release of the program.


  Of course those with 'Catcomp' can feel free to just upload any
  translated AmCEx.ct and .catalog files to Aminet under the name of:

      @{fg shine}util/conv/AmCurrency_XX.lha@{fg text}

  where the XX stands for the language descriptor, such as IT for Italy
  or CA for Canada. It could even be stretched to 3 letters, ie USA, but
  that is the limit of Aminet file naming conventions.



@ENDNODE


